My DMs and my comment section is full of women asking what sunscreen to use when they are pregnant or when they’re breastfeeding?? 🤷🏻‍♀️

Well, the answer is mineral sunscreens. ✨

Chemical sunscreen are best avoided during pregnancy, so it’s important to check the ingredient list of the sunscreen you are using. 

You can try the @orimiiskincare SPF 50 sunscreen. This one is 100% mineral sunscreen, specifically designed for pregnant females and mothers who were breastfeeding. 

And the best part is unlike all the other mineral sunscreen, this one does not leave behind any white cast and is very lightweight and easy to use . 

Give it a try .♥️

#drshivangirana #dermatologist #collab

📌 So, how should you really approach skincare?

✨ Well, firstly, make sure that it is not something you’re buying on the basis of packaging or overly marketed claims. 

✨ Give equal importance to formulations as well . 
For example, while looking for a hyaluronic acid moisturiser, look for other natural moisturising factors like electrolytes as well, that will help the moisturiser perform better. 

✨ Lastly, please stop jumping from one skincare to the other. You need to give enough time to each skincare product for it to show results. ♥️

#Beautytoascience #NeutrogenaHydroBoost #watergel #moisturiser #skincareroutine #skincare

🌸 Want to treat hyperpigmentation? 

Stay away from creams containing Hydroquinone, Tretinoin or steroids. 
They can seriously ruin your face. 

🧚🏻‍♀️ Instead prefer creams with Kojic acid, Niacinamide, and tranexamic acid. 

These are much safer ingredients to help lighten pigmentation and uneven skin tone.✨

Recommendations-

• Demelan cream 
• Ilumax Ultra. 
• Brilante skin brightening serum 
• Tyrodin cream. 

📌 How to use? 

Start with alternate night application, can be build Upto daily application. 
Don’t forget your sunscreen the next day.♥️

Hope it helps. ♥️

#drshivangirana #dermatologist

✨ Glowy skin, glossy hair and pretty feet with little effort?

Really low maintenance habits that can make you look high maintenance. 🤷🏻‍♀️

1️⃣. Foot peels- takes 1/1.5 hrs every 2-3 months and all tanning and uneven pigmentation gone.

Avoid them if any active injury , any infection or dermatological skin condition on the foot or uncontrolled diabetes.
